Application: French COVID-19 Data

Today, letâ€™s look at an application using data from the COVID-19 pandemic in France. Weâ€™ll see some more pandemic data in the coming weeks. Today we will use several data sets. Load them in below and take a moment to look at them.

covid <- read_csv("data/france_departement_covid.csv")
pop <- read_csv("data/france_departement_population.csv")
cities <- read_csv("data/france_cities.csv")
geo_fr <- read_sf("data/france_departement.geojson") %>%
  filter(departement <= "95")

To get started, produce a basic spatial plot of the geo_fr data:

geo_fr %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_sf()

Now, filter the dataset covid to the date â€œ2020-05-01â€ and left join it into the geo_fr dataset by the key â€œdepartementâ€. Just have the data print out to the notebook.

covid %>%
  filter(date == "2020-05-01") %>%
  left_join(geo_fr, by = "departement")

Now, starting with the code that you created above, plot a map of the French DÃ©partement according to the the number of people that were hospitalized on 1 May 2020. Use scale_fill_distiller to pick a good color scale.

covid %>%
  filter(date == "2020-05-01") %>%
  left_join(geo_fr, by = "departement") %>%
  st_as_sf() %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_sf(aes(fill = hospitalised)) +
    scale_fill_distiller(
      trans = "log2", palette = "Spectral", guide = "legend", n.breaks = 10
    )

A problem with the above map is that it is not normalized by population. Adapt the code above in the block below by joining in the pop dataset and instead plotting the hospitalization rate were 100k people.

covid %>%
  filter(date == "2020-05-01") %>%
  left_join(geo_fr, by = "departement") %>%
  left_join(pop, by = "departement") %>%
  mutate(rate = hospitalised / population * 100000) %>%
  st_as_sf() %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_sf(aes(fill = rate)) +
    scale_fill_distiller(
      trans = "log2", palette = "Spectral", guide = "legend", n.breaks = 10
    )

We also have a data set of French cities called cities. Create a spatial points version of the cities data and save it as an object called cities_geo.

cities_geo <- cities %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c("lon", "lat"), crs = 4326, remove = FALSE)

Now, put together the hopsitalization rate map with the cities data in a single plot. Include both points and text labels for the cities.

covid %>%
  filter(date == "2020-05-01") %>%
  left_join(geo_fr, by = "departement") %>%
  left_join(pop, by = "departement") %>%
  mutate(rate = hospitalised / population * 100000) %>%
  st_as_sf() %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_sf(aes(fill = rate), alpha = 0.8) +
    geom_sf(data = cities_geo) +
    geom_sf_text(aes(label = city), data = cities_geo, nudge_y = 0.1, size = 6) +
    scale_fill_distiller(
      trans = "log2", palette = "Spectral", guide = "legend", n.breaks = 10
    )

As a final task, we want to create a plot that includes both the states and the highways. However, we only want to include highways that contain some part of one of the highways in our data. This is slightly more difficult that it may appear at first, so letâ€™s walk through it together.

Start by creating a data set called hwy_with_state that joins hwy to the state data.

hwy_with_state <- hwy %>%
  spatial_join(state)

Now, we want to create a data set called state_in_hwy from a semi join of state with hwy_with_state. R wonâ€™t let us do this directly though because we are not allowed to do a semi join with two spatial datasets directly. Instead, we first need to create a non-spatial version of hwy_with_state with this code:

hwy_with_state_tbl <- hwy_with_state %>%
  as_tibble() %>%
  select(-geometry)

Now, create state_in_hwy as a semi join between state and hwy_with_state_tbl:

state_in_hwy <- state %>%
  semi_join(hwy_with_state_tbl, by = "state")

Now, create the desired plot using hwy_with_state and state_in_hwy. Take a moment to try to make the plot look nice.

hwy_with_state %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_sf(data = state_in_hwy, color = "grey50", fill = "grey90") +
    geom_sf(aes(color = state), size = 1.5)
